You've hard-coded a lot of the virtual media configuration here. Not all platforms will want to support these six channels.

We have infrastructure to configure and describe the available virtual media channels already, which can also handle arbitrary data about those channels (for example, if you want to provide user-readable information - like whether they're CD or HDD types).

That's configured through the nbd-proxy's config.json; the "metadata" key in that json can be updated with whatever data you would like to describe the channels.

Then, if you execute:

    nbd-proxy --metadata

you'll get a small json fragment with the channel configurations - which, of course, includes the number of channels. I suggest you use that information to populate your channel datastructures here.

If course, you could read the underlying config.json directly if you prefer, but that includes more than just the metadata fields.

> Rather than having both present, but only one available, why not just remove (with #ifdef) the non-sdr-dbus handlers when the sdr-dbus handlers are enabled?

But this is up to you on how we want to support it.

Regarding applying to all network calls: I spoke with Vernon about this prior to pushing this commit. There is some hesitancy to applying this generically at the dispatch function. It's hard to guarantee that the Invalid Argument exception means the same thing for all possible IPMI calls.

I can think of two approaches to the problem:
1. Have the dispatch code collect Invalid Argument exceptions, for all commands. Then if a command needs some other handling catch the exception in the variant command.
2. Explicitly catch the Invalid Argument exception in every IPMI command.

In either case there is work to be done for effectively every IPMI command, network related or not.
